Package net.xqhs.flash.core.util

Class MultiValueMap

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.xqhs.util.config.Config
      • net.xqhs.flash.core.util.MultiValueMap
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, net.xqhs.util.config.Configurable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AgentEvent, MultiTreeMap, RegisteredParameterSet
    public class MultiValueMap
extends net.xqhs.util.config.Config
implements java.io.Serializable
    The class acts as a collection of key-value pairs that allows multiple values for the same key (also called name).

    For convenience and readability, String values are special and are added and retrieved using separate methods than for Object values (we call Object values those values which are of any other type than String). A name can have both String and Object values associated, but some methods may fail if values are not accessed correctly.

    null values are allowed, but get methods also return null when names are not found.

    It is implemented as a map with String keys and with values that are a List of Objects. Using a map improves finding entries. Using a list instead of a set ensures that entries with the same key stay in the same order as added, which may be an advantage.

    Historically, this functionality was achieved as a set of String-Object entries, but that was not as efficient. Functionality is the same, except that the order of values for the same key is maintained.

    The class is backed by a LinkedHashMap with String keys and LinkedLists of Objects.

    The class extends Config and can be locked so that no changes are made thereon. However, the Config.ConfigLockedException thrown by locked methods is converted to a RuntimeException instance.

    This implementation is not synchronized. Any methods returning a collection of values/objects return collections that are not backed up by the multi-map.

    Author:
    Andrei Olaru
